<table width="540" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">

<tr><td>
<!-- content starts here --> 

<font class="body">
<table width="100%" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" border="0">
<tr align=left>
	<td colspan=2><font class="pressReleaseTitle">
		<b>Home Networking Supersession Debates State of the Industry, Future Possibilities</b></font></td></tr>
<tr align=left>
	<td colspan=2><font class="pressReleaseSubTitle">
		<b></b></font><hr noshade size=1></td></tr>
<!--
<tr><td bgcolor="000000" colspan=2><hr noshade size=2></td></tr>
-->
<tr><td align=left><font class="pressReleaseLocation">
		<b>Las Vegas,NV</b></font></td>
	<td align=right><font class="pressReleaseDate">
		1/9/01</font></td></tr>
<tr><td colspan=2><hr noshade size=2></td></tr>
<!--
<tr><td bgcolor="000000" colspan=2><hr noshade size=1></td></tr>
-->
</table>

<table cellpadding=0 cellspacing=0 border=0 width=80%>
<tr><td>&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;</td>
	<td><font class="pressReleaseBody">Attendees to the 2001 International CES - Your Source for Workstyle and Lifestyle Technology - flocked to yesterday’s Home Networking Supersession, where the capacity crowd heard a panel of experts candidly discuss the present and future state of the home networking industry.  During the one-and-a-half-hour session, Julie Jacobson, panel moderator and editor of Home Networking News, led the discussion through a series of topics including the role of Internet appliances in home networking, service issues, standards debates and ”killer applications.”<p>The panel was composed of several respected industry experts from the manufacturing and retail communities, and included Tom Hite, chief technology officer for Panja, Inc.; Dave Martella, vice president, Emerging Technologies & Strategic Development for RadioShack; Julie Shimer, vice president and general manager, Residential Connectivity Group of the Personal Connectivity Business Unit; 3Com Corp.; and Harold ”Tom” Tomlinson, chairman of the Universal Plug-and-Play Appliance Working Group, GE Corporate Research and Development.  <p>Jacobson set the tone for a lively discussion by performing a ”rap” detailing the current state of the home networking industry, with a particular focus on the numerous competing standards. <p>While the discussion covered numerous topics, it was clear that certain items were of particular importance to both the audience and the panel, with technical and service issues, the standards debate and the factors influencing consumer adoption receiving the most attention.<p>To highlight the convergence of technology in the home, the CES is showcasing smart appliances and the consumer benefits of interconnectivity through keynote addresses, executive briefings, supersessions and home networking exhibits. <p>The sessions on the home networking track cover issues such as Bluetooth technology and interconnectivity, smart appliances and the interactive household, set-top boxes, 1394 and the impact of audio and video convergence.<p>The Classification and Phasing of Networks Panel was moderated by Christian Jorgensen, Technology Evangelist, Sony Electronics, Inc. and featured lively discussion among panelists: Matthew Swanston, Manager of Communications, CEA; Kara Dickerson, Manager of Member Relations, CEA; Peter Lesser, President, X-10; and William Rose, Chairman, CEA’s R-7 Technology and Standards Committee.  CEA Home Networks and IT Division board member Jorgensen began the discussion by announcing the launch of CEA’s Industry Guide to Home Networks.  The online handbook will serve as the definitive resource for technical, application and classification information on home networks. <p>”The home network has evolved from its roots in automation and security and has come to include the distribution of information and entertainment content throughout the home,” explained Lesser during the panel discussion.  ”However, this rapid evolution has left many of the terms and much of the industry undefined and unexplained.  As the trade association that represents all of the products and interests involved with the home network, CEA has undertaken the task of defining the terms the industry will use to classify and develop home networks.” <p>Spearheaded by CEA’s HNIT Division, the guide was assembled from materials submitted by industry entrepreneurs, company presidents, product engineers, industry research analysts and CEA staff.  The Industry Guide to Home Networks is currently posted on www.CE.org/networkguide.<p>While CES encompasses four exhibit facilities, most of the home networking exhibits are located in the north hall of the Las Vegas Convention Center and in the Las Vegas Hilton.  There also are several pavilions covering the latest in home networking and the digital home, including the Home Security Pavilion, Upside’s Digital Living Room Pavilion, the 1394 Pavilion and the Digital Subscriber Line (DSL) Pavilion.  <p>For more news on CES before, during and after the show, visit www.CESweb.org, the interactive source for CES information.<p>CEA represents more than 600 U.S. companies involved in the development, manufacturing and distribution of audio, video, mobile electronics, communications, information technology, multimedia and accessory products, as well as related services, that are sold through consumer channels.  Combined, these companies account for more than $60 billion in annual sales.<p>CEA also sponsors and manages the International CES - Your Source for Workstyle and Lifestyle Technology.  All profits from CES are reinvested into industry services, including technical training and education, industry promotion, engineering standards development, market research and legislative advocacy.<br></font></td></tr>



